segments.text: This is the morning of November the 6th.
I am in the lovely home of Professor Emeritus C.A.
Bonnen, who is a member of the Department of Agricultural Economics at Texas A&M University, although he has been retired for many years.
He retired, he says, in 1961, but we are most anxious to get his response to some important questions, to capitalize on his rich experience.
So CA, what I'd like to do is just ask you to respond to a few questions, and you just
Give us your recollections of these things.
You grew up on a farm in central Illinois.
Born, you said, in 1896, so this was the turn of the century and the first decade into this new century.
What was farm life like then?
Well, it was pretty hard work.
Tractors were just coming in.
They weren't in general use.
Of course, there were still a majority of the farm power.
And that's the most I recall of it.
I left the farm right after I graduated from the university.
anything I'd say about corn at that time, which was 1920.
Did you harvest the corn by hand picking then?
Yeah.
Entirely, wasn't it?
Did they have the wheel plow?
Did you have a wheel plow or was it a hand plow?
Do you recall?
Did the plows have wheels?
Yes.
And you rode on them or were they hand plows?
They had wheel plows.
So you did have some relatively modern technology, didn't you?
Yeah, such as it was.
Did you have livestock besides the horses?
Oh yes.
Did you feed cattle or did you have hogs mostly?
We had dairy cattle.
So you think there's been a lot of changes in that farm in Illinois, hasn't there, C.A.?
I imagine there has.
Yeah.
When did you last get back to Illinois to see the farming?
Oh, right after I graduated from the university and that was 1920.
I see.
Well, the size of the farms are much, much larger.
My family moved off the farm and moved to Urbana at that time.
Well, what contributions do you believe that agricultural research
As you've experienced it over the years, not just economics, but the whole agricultural research, what contributions has that made to farming in Illinois and Texas?
Within what period?
Since you were on that farm.
That's right up until now.
Right up until now.
I haven't been back there to see what they've done.
I'm sure it's changed a lot.
Farms are larger, more power to use, all that sort of thing.
I'm worried about changes.
During those earlier years of your professional life, you were heavily involved in farm management research.
and you were able to see some of the changes that were occurring in the way those farms were managed and operated.
I'd really like to get your recollections of those kinds of changes.
Well, of course there's been a lot of changes, especially in the older farming areas.
The big change has been in the areas like East Texas, where we've practically gone out of farming.
I don't plan to change ownership.
Ownership is in the hands of people that used to live in Houston and places like that.
Very little farming done.
It's mostly forestry.
sort of thing.

In the other areas of Texas where farming is still going on, in the rolling plains, in the black lands, you've seen less dramatic changes in the sense that agriculture, the farming hasn't gone out of the areas, but
What kind of changes did you see taking place while you were involved in research?
Well, I recall that there was more irrigation on the plains and wherever they could get water.
And of course, the types of farming
further west you go, the tax of farming are pretty much the same.
All it has changed is the power and that sort of thing.
Do you feel that our profession of agricultural economics, and particularly in farm management, made some real contributions to agriculture in those years?
It's pretty hard to say.
Changes have taken place regardless, you know.
I imagine we had some influence on me.
As you look back, and this may not be a fair question to ask anybody, but you've had a chance to reflect on the profession and what you were doing.
Do you see any areas where you think we missed the boat?
Some things we ought to have done as agricultural economists and in farm management
that we didn't do or things that we did incorrectly, inadequately?
That's some question.
I suppose there were some things that we should have done that we didn't do, but that would have been true of any group that existed at that time.
We're all subject to change.
Yes.
How much change we would have made if we had known more than we did is a question even today.
I think all these changes would have taken place whether we were here or not.
Yes, they might have taken place differently had they not had access to our

your studies see we our plan of studying the agriculture of texas was first a general study of the whole state and we drove 5 500 miles within the state to delineate those areas which i believe you've asked about and
We spent a whole month making their trips through the state and checking the delineations and so on.
And I believe you remarked that they were still about the same.
Yes, one of the remarkable things that has occurred to me as I've looked back at that very classic study that you and
a few of your colleagues made, you were certainly the prime mover in that study.
And what impresses me is that after all these years, there's been very little change in the delineation of those types of farming.
Yeah, of course.
We had to begin with Dr. Carter's soil divisions, and we just refined
and added an area here and there that seems different.
And as they are today, you can look up his reports and see the difference.
Well, that's of most interest.
Reflecting a little bit on how our profession has changed
in terms of graduate study at the institution.
You first pursued graduate study at the University of Illinois in the 1920s.
Then later in the 1930s, you did a year of graduate study at the Giannini Foundation and at the University of California at Berkeley.
I'd be very much interested in getting your recollections
of those individuals from whom you got classes and what the graduate study concentrated on at that time?
Well, at Illinois, Professor Hanson, I don't know if you ever heard of him or not, he died rather young.
He was head of the department.
It was he that really steered me into the economics of the situation.
And then California HR Polley was head of the HR department.
And that's why I went there to graduate.
He was a very fine individual.
I got most of my so-called information from him and his associates.
Who were some of the others?
Was Adams, Professor Adams in farm management?
He was there, but he didn't contribute much.
He was kind of...
behind the times.
I see.
Several others complained.
He used an electric system and he got very little out of it.
But H.R.
Tolley was there too.
Yes.
And of course he saved the day and brought us into the so-called presence.
Yes.
Presence.
Do you recall some of the others that were there at any foundation at that time?
I'm trying to think of his name.
He was head of the department at South Dakota when I was there.
Benedict.
Yes, Murray Benedict.
Now, Murray did his later work in agricultural policy.
I don't know what he was doing at that time.
I didn't follow him very closely after he got out there.
Polly was a big influence.
Yes, influence in getting you there, and he was the one who most influenced you while you were there, when you were thinking.
Was there anyone else at Illinois besides Professor Hanson that you recall in those early days?
No, not that I...
No, I didn't.
Then you were on the faculty at South Dakota State for two years, and I understand that you were one of the
of T.W.
Schultz's earliest professors of agricultural economics.
That's right.
He's probably the most famous of our entire profession, and you've had an influence very early in his professional life.
Ted has always given me more credit than I deserve.
Well, I've regarded him as an honest man.
But what was your impression of him when he was an undergraduate student?
Well, he was older than the average student and an outstanding individual.
But I had a class of about 12 boys at that time, and they were all young, bright individuals.
I've never had a class like this.
more outstanding than they were.
And I wish I had kept up with them so that I could see what happened, but I didn't.
I live in Chicago, Dakota right now.
But you were able, you think, to sense in Ted Schultz as a student, somebody who had all the ingredients of greatness.
Yeah, right from the beginning.
Yeah, that's interesting.
Well, we've talked about some of the early research.
You didn't get heavily into research until you got down here, I guess.
You did some at South Dakota in those two years, but in farm management, type of farming studies.
Was that where you first began to work with Buck Elliott?
Yeah, he was a friend of mine.
He was at the USDA in Washington, or was he in Washington?
He was in Washington, but you collaborated with him on research while you were at South Dakota.
Very interesting.
He was a fine individual.
He didn't live long enough.
I see.
What was it that brought you to Texas?
Mr. Gabbard was head of the department here.
Yes.
And, uh, Buck Elliott happened to come down here right at the time, and he was looking for somebody to take the job of farm management.
And, uh, when Mr. Gabbard mentioned it to him,
He immediately recommended me.
Very interesting.
That drastically altered both your personal and professional life, didn't it?
Oh, yeah.
And this is a very primitive area when I came here.
Yes.
We had a hard time finding a place to live and all that sort of stuff.
Well, uh-huh.
Was it simply because the area was growing faster than they had, they had prepared for, or?
Well, my impression of it was that it hadn't grown fast enough.
The housing was poor and all that.
Yes.
And we had much better housing in South Dakota than we had down here.
Yes.
I never thought about it.
I never know what Alice really thought about it.
Yes.
Did she ever question whether or not you made the right choice in coming to Texas?
She never questioned anything.
I see.
Well, one of the bright spots of
Mrs. Hopkin, my life is getting to know her.
We got to know her through your granddaughters, but she was a remarkable woman.
Well, you landed down here, and as I understand it, you were very quickly caught up into this research on type of farming areas.
The first thing I did when I came here.
I see, that was your first assignment.
And that was your plan to do that for all of the areas of the state?
But it never got completed?
What interrupted that?
Well, I don't think any individual or person had anything to do with it.
I think it was the circumstances of time.
There were too many areas.
Too many areas.
Then the Depression.
Yeah, the Depression hit us.
Came along with all of those serious problems.
Are you all, well, how, let me not give the answer to the question, just pose a question.
How did the Depression hit Texas as compared to, say, other areas?
Was it as hard down here or harder?
Do you have some feeling on that?
I think it's a matter of development.
I think...
So that the agriculture was just beginning to unfold
and develop when you really got here in the 20s.
Your research activities at Texas A&M involved you very heavily in research on the severe economic depression
which agriculture was undergoing during the 20s and all the 30s, through that whole New Deal farm adjustment programs, that were designed, I guess, to help farmers just survive, wasn't it?
Well, I don't know that we thought of it in those terms, that some of them were going to survive anyway, anyhow, any way you did it.
There was quite a bit of effort at that time to get people to think in terms of these areas and that sort of thing.
And the whole institution was pulled into the Extension Service and the Experiment Station.
Mr. Connor was director of the Experiment Station and he didn't
He didn't have a whole lot of interest in it, as I saw it.
But I attended all meetings with him.
And I guess he was a spokesman for the Experiment Station.
And the young fellow in the Extension Service was very much more advanced in his thinking.
Who was this?
Do you recall his name?
Bill Morgan.
Bill Morgan?
Yes, yes.
He went to Colorado.
He went to Colorado as president of Colorado State University, didn't he?
Mm-hmm.
He was a really young man.
Yes.
I was proud to be associated.
Mm-hmm.
But as you, as you, you got caught up into, in this...
this change, trying to help farmers adjust, and one of the ideas was to really follow the type of farming that was applicable to the area they were in.
Was that?
Yes.
Farmer under certain circumstances.
Certain type of land and all that sort of thing.
He tried to think of his problems as different from the area next to him.
Now, you were kind of the lone social scientist in that group, weren't you?
Well, Bill Morgan, you said, was the young extension.
Did you have problems with the physical scientists getting them to see the economic problems?
Well, I don't remember much about that, but I thought you meant that we have much trouble with the extension people and people like that.
But this fellow, Bill Morgan, was a favorite of the extension director.
And that made it easy to...
I see.
Well, that's good.
Williamson was a
That's when Williamson was Director of the Extension Service.
Mr. Connery was Director of the Experimental Space.
We were all separate at that time.
I think it was 42 when we crowded into one department.
Now, as you began to address these problems of the Depression,
there were lots of new agencies emerged.
Oh, the AAA resettlement.
You were quite heavily involved, were you not, you and some of your colleagues, in this AAA work, as I understand some of the comments of Professor Gabbard and
and others.
Yes, that's what I understand, but there were some real problems of working with the government people and others in really getting the FIPL-A organized, and then learning how to operate it.
Do you recall some of your experiences associated with that?
I don't, uh, I think it was, as far as I was concerned, it was in the 80's, my, this fella, Morgan, who was in good favor with the extension director.
We, uh, we just went right along.
Had no great difficulty.
He was here during the 30s then, as a young guy.
I guess I got to meet him just about the time he went to
Colorado State University.
And he was, what, maybe less than 50?
Oh, yeah.
He went up there and he was in his 30s.
Was he?
Mm-hmm.
Right.
Because that would be in the late 40s, when he, or about 47 or 8 when he went up there, I expect, or 46.
But I have no recollection of the time.
Do you want to go ahead and take the film?
Well, Professor Bonin, we've just been visiting a little bit about all of your involvement when the AAA was initiated along with other programs to help farmers during the Depression.
I'd surely appreciate it
all you can recollect about how this program operated.
It began, what, in 19, about 1933?
Now, how was the university or the experiment station involved?
It was really the experiment station, not the university, wasn't it?
Well, the experiment station, see, at that time it was a separate
organization.
And the two of them were both involved in this operation.
Who ran that program?
Do you recall?
Did the statewide operation run out of Bryan College Station?
I don't remember.
Washington background.
Yes.
And the two directors were brought in together.
And we had to get along all right that way.
I don't remember we had any great difficulty.
There may have been some, but I didn't know any about it.
Yes.
Do you recall the important...
problems that had to be resolved that called for research skills in agricultural economics and farm management.
We didn't think of them as being separate problems.
Yes.
They were just problems we had to meet at the time.
You just had to solve problems.
What were some of those problems as you now recall them?
There were problems of supply control and marketing privileges, I guess, as I recall.
How did they control the marketing of cotton?
Did they destroy a lot of bales of cotton, or did they simply control how they marketed it?
I don't recall any actual destruction.
Yes.
They simply cut back on acreage.
They tried to.
All they ever cut back on was the acreage that didn't produce much anyway.
Yes.
That's when they learned how to do that, I guess.
They've been doing it ever since.
Yeah.
And it led to...
use of more fertilizer and that sort of thing, so they didn't gain much.
Production didn't cut back very much.
Now, tell us more about your involvement.
Why, what did you have to... You mean the AAA effort?
Yes, in that AAA effort.
In the latter part of paragraph six, you didn't think of this problem being economic or whatever it was.
I recall visiting with your son Jim one time about this period.
He was a young man in the home, a young boy maybe, but he says he recalls
You're getting calls in the middle of the night.
What would those calls be about?
I'd say they had these certificates.
One of them had a certain value.
And if they misplaced one of them, they'd call me.
Ask me where it was.
Were you in charge of issuing those certificates?
or who these were issued, I'm sure, by the AAA committees, I suspect.
The AAA.
I was caught right in the middle of it.
Well, was this operated from Texas A&M?
Well, we were involved, but I don't know who had the final yes or no.
Was it located on campus, the handling of the certificates and all these things were moved right on campus?
Right on the campus.
I see.
So the Extension Service particularly and the Experiment Station were intimately involved in the operation of that program at that time.
That's right.
That's interesting.
Do you recall any kinds of legal problems arose out
some of these controlled efforts?
I don't know whether they were legal or illegal.
We used to be a man here by the name of Weddington.
Yes.
He was chief clerk in the Extension Service and a very influential individual.
And as these problems developed,
He and I became very good friends.
And he was a very upright, very good man.
And he could straighten out things from extension supports.
I see.
Every organization ought to have somebody like that.
Somebody like that.
So that would be...
He was a big man, a big tall fellow.
Yeah.
So, between him on the one hand and Bill Morgan on the other, you had a lot of help.
That's right.
Did you get to know Sam McMillan in the Extension Service?
Do you recall him?
in farm management.
He was very active in the early development of teaching farm management, and then he went with the Extension Service for a little while.
Then finally with the Farm Security when they got organized during the Depression.
Uh-huh.
Okay.
The name kind of flickers around in my mind,
I see.
In the work that you were doing.
Yes.
That's interesting.
Well, I suspect we may never experience again those new experimental days of the AAA and the Depression.

We probably don't have the, we probably don't, first, we may not have the serious problem arise again that was then, but we're probably too constrained by tradition now to, if we did face those serious problems, to experiment as you folks experimented.
I hope they don't.
We don't have them.
Why do you say that?
Well, I guess two or three o'clock calls in the morning and that sort of thing wouldn't go so good now.
Yes.
During the 30s, there were many more changes made in agricultural policy.
federal programs for agriculture than at any other time in our history, probably.
Of course, as you've mentioned, there was some serious economic problems emerged all during the 20s.
The kind of research that you were doing, were you
And Mr. Gabbard involved very much in providing information that was useful to the policymakers, administrators who were making and administering farm policy as those policies emerged in the 30s.
Well, that's what we were thinking about.
Yes.
to what extent they influenced people's thinking, it would be hard to say.
Well, I suspect you're, as others have told me, you're a very modest man.
Well, I never had a feeling of
I never had a feeling of control over these things.
Yes, well, I can understand that.
Yet the kind of research that you were doing relating to identifying the problems associated with farm management, managing these farms for profit,
likely had a substantial impact on... Well, it may have had.
We never felt like we controlled very much.
When you would make these studies in CA,
Did you work throughout the year?
Would you be out in the state all during the time?
You had a field man out in there, out in the field.
Did you know A.C. McGee?
Yes, I knew A.C. McGee.
He was field man for about five years out on the High Plains.
At Lubbock or operating out of Lubbock?
He operated out of Lubbock.
The High Plains area included...
the cotton producing part of the pipelines.
And he lived in Lubbock and had, I don't know, maybe 50 farmers that worked with him.
And he visited them regularly.
He visited them regularly and got details of the operation.
Farm costs.
Did they sort of keep
They kept records.
Kept detailed records for him.
They used a simple form of record book that I designed for the state of Texas.
That's about all I remember, but he was a good man on detail.
Yes.
We depended on him as our contact.
The idea, when we first made this type of farming study, the idea was that eventually we would get around to all the areas, which turned out to be impossible.
But we did get to, I guess, four or five of them.
Plans are always bigger than your output.
Well, that's appropriate, I'm sure.
We all have to plan too big and then strain ourselves to get all of it we can.
During that particular time, of course, your research unit was totally separated from the teaching.
Did you ever have any graduate students
that worked for you on their dissertations or their thesis?
No.
They didn't?
Those were never, never were related together.
That's... That was until 1942.
Yes.
What's it mean?
Gilchrist became president, nodded two heads around and brought everything together.
Yes.
And I say, knock their heads around.
Yes.
Some of them had to be hit a little hard to do that.
You know, I never saw as much difference in a man who went from in charge of the whole institution.
See, he was the, what do you call him?
Chancellor?
The president?
Chancellor, I guess.
Chancellor, yeah.
He could knock anybody's head around.
Yes.
And...
Later on, after he retired, while he was chancellor, I couldn't even give a word.
But after he retired, I walked a good deal, and he did too.
And I'd run into him out here in South Kansas or something.
And I couldn't hardly get away from him.
And he would talk to me.
That's interesting.
Showed what kind of man he was.
Yes.
He concentrated on his job.
Well, he was too big.
Yes.
Well, how did the problems change for you and in your research as we moved toward the end of the 30s?
into 1940 and 41, and war preparations came on us in about 1940 and 41, and then the end of 41 we were in World War II.
What happened to your programs then?
Did this change your research program very much?
Well, it didn't change our thinking about it.
not the program we had, we still have in mind, after we had developed these type farming areas, making individual studies in each area.
Of course, that never happened except in four or five areas.
But during the war,
Was there, were you and the Extension Service as well as the Experiment Station
